article.description:
Allison Feaster scored 11 of her 13 points in the
second half Friday, helping the Charlotte Sting recover from
blowing a 20-point halftime lead before defeating the Miami Sol 72-68.
article.headline: Stinson leads Sting's first-half charge
article.linkText: Sting hold off Sol after blowing 20-point lead
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Allison Feaster scored 11 of her 13 points in the second half Friday, helping the Charlotte Sting recover from blowing a 20-point halftime lead before defeating the Miami Sol 72-68. Andrea Stinson scored 16 of her 18 points in the first half for Charlotte (8-7), which won for the second time in eight road games this season. Tammy Sutton-Brown added 16 points and nine rebounds for the Sting. Sandy Brondello scored a season-high 23 points for Miami (5-10), which had its season-high three-game winning streak snapped. Sheri Sam had 15 of her 19 points after halftime for the Sol. "Any win is a good win on the road,'' Charlotte coach Anne Donovan said. "We kept our focus for 40 minutes and that's what you have to do when you're on the road.'' The Sting led 41-21 at halftime, holding the Sol to a season-low 25.9 percent shooting in the first half -- one game after Miami shot a franchise-record 55.7 percent in a win over Phoenix on Wednesday. "It was very disappointing the way we started the game,'' Brondello said. "The second half showed what we are capable of and now we need to get that into a full game.'' Miami opened the second half on a 21-2 run, hitting nine of its first 14 shots from the floor. The Sol took their first second-half lead, 51-50, on a Sam jumper with 7:32 left. Charlotte quickly reclaimed control with a 10-2 run, the final five points coming from Feaster, to take a 60-53 lead with 3:21 remaining. The Sol never seriously threatened again. "Anytime you play a team on their home court, they're going to have their run,'' Stinson said. "I think we did a great job withstanding it.'' Stinson scored nine points in a 20-0 first-half run by Charlotte, which took a 26-5 lead with 9:19 remaining in the half. "We came in a little cocky,'' Sol center P.J. Kimbrough said. "We kind of got away from the things we had been doing.'' Charlotte shot 54.8 percent in the first half and outrebounded Miami 21-8 in the first 20 minutes. The Sting shot just 26.9 percent in the second half. "Charlotte had just lost a game at home and came in here ready to prove a point,'' Sol coach Ron Rothstein said. "I'm not too sure we didn't come in here a little too comfortable with ourselves.'' Charlotte made seven 3-pointers, its season high away from home this season. The Sting are shooting 50.0 percent on 3s at home, but just 29.7 percent on the road. Game notes
Miami guard Debbie Black was charged with a turnover with 25.7 seconds left in the first half, her first in 108 minutes. Black had 18 assists during the turnover-free streak. ... Charlotte missed its first nine shots of the second half. ... Sol reserve Betty Lennox had averaged 16.6 points in her last five games, but finished with two points on 1-for-9 shooting Friday. ... Miami has never won a game when trailing by more than eight points at halftime. The WNBA record for a halftime comeback is 18.
